00:04:51.271 --> 00:04:57.201
The most famous of these is Burns Night, which is a celebration of the life of

00:04:57.201 --> 00:05:03.671
the famous Scottish poet Robert Burns, and falls on January 25th every year.

00:05:05.101 --> 00:05:09.701
But what you might not know, and is certainly an unusual

00:05:09.721 --> 00:05:14.231
Scottish tradition, is what is done before the haggis is eaten.

00:05:15.541 --> 00:05:20.551
The haggis is prepared, of course, which really only means boiling it in water.

00:05:21.321 --> 00:05:24.921
It is brought to the table, ideally to the sound of bagpipes.

00:05:25.511 --> 00:05:27.871
I have piped in many a haggis, I should add.

00:05:29.141 --> 00:05:36.521
But before the haggis can be eaten, it is tradition to read a poem to celebrate the haggis.

00:05:37.481 --> 00:05:42.811
It was written by Robert Burns himself, and is called “Address to a Haggis”.

00:05:44.271 --> 00:05:48.811
It is written in Scots, so it is hard to understand, even

00:05:48.811 --> 00:05:52.661
for a native English speaker, but it starts like this:

00:05:53.931 --> 00:05:56.431
Fair fa’ your honest, sonsie face,

00:05:56.731 --> 00:05:59.181
Great Chieftain o’ the Puddin-race!

00:06:00.158 --> 00:06:02.508
I imagine you might not have understood any of that.

00:06:03.248 --> 00:06:09.718
“ Fair fa” is a way of wishing someone well and “sonsie” means happy or cheerful.

00:06:10.558 --> 00:06:16.218
And then he is calling the haggis a “chieftain”, a great leader, of the race of puddings.

00:06:16.968 --> 00:06:21.128
So to translate it into normal English, it would be something like:

00:06:21.718 --> 00:06:24.058
Hello, honest and happy haggis,

00:06:24.388 --> 00:06:26.738
You wonderful leader of all puddings.

00:06:27.468 --> 00:06:33.278
Anyway, I won’t go through the entire poem, it’s quite long and complicated, but about

00:06:33.308 --> 00:06:40.448
a third of the way through the poem the person reading it needs to ceremoniously stab

00:06:40.518 --> 00:06:46.328
the haggis with a knife, cutting it open and spilling all the contents of the pudding.

00:06:47.178 --> 00:06:54.108
It is a lot of fun, and if you ever find yourself in Scotland on Burns Night and see an animated

00:06:54.108 --> 00:07:00.718
person reading a poem out loud and holding a large knife, do not worry, this is what is going on.

