Now, for our second unusual tradition, we are going to talk about something called The

00:07:08.238 --> 00:07:13.658
Highland Games, and you will be pleased to hear that haggises feature here as well.

00:07:14.778 --> 00:07:19.068
The Highlands, as you may know, are the northern half of Scotland.

00:07:19.878 --> 00:07:22.468
If you have seen pictures of wonderful mountains and

00:07:22.468 --> 00:07:25.408
forests, you are probably imagining the Highlands.

00:07:26.408 --> 00:07:30.898
And during the summer months, all throughout the Highlands, different

00:07:30.948 --> 00:07:35.838
towns and villages put on “Highland Games”, which are a sort of day of

00:07:36.068 --> 00:07:40.418
sporting activities and competitions, as well as music and celebrations.

00:07:41.348 --> 00:07:46.758
Some of the events will be familiar to you: there are normally running races

00:07:46.758 --> 00:07:53.058
and weight lifting, but some of the activities will probably be less familiar.

00:07:53.918 --> 00:07:58.378
There is something called “tossing the caber”, which involves picking up a

00:07:58.388 --> 00:08:05.378
large telegraph pole, a huge pole of wood, typically 5 to 6 metres tall, and

00:08:05.458 --> 00:08:10.648
throwing it so that it lands on one end and then flips over on the other.

00:08:11.908 --> 00:08:15.568
There is the hammer throw, which involves someone trying to

00:08:15.578 --> 00:08:19.388
launch a heavy ball attached to a rope as far as they can.

00:08:20.078 --> 00:08:24.688
It's quite scary and impressive to watch, as the person needs to spin around

00:08:24.688 --> 00:08:29.588
and around and then let go of the rope just at the right time so that it

00:08:29.598 --> 00:08:33.838
doesn’t fly into the crowd and smash into some unsuspecting spectator.

00:08:35.178 --> 00:08:39.168
And then there is also something called “hurling the haggis”.

00:08:39.898 --> 00:08:46.308
To hurl is another word for to throw, it means to throw with great force or effort.

00:08:47.328 --> 00:08:51.798
And haggis hurling is exactly that, it requires

00:08:51.798 --> 00:08:55.478
someone to throw a haggis as far as they possibly can.

00:08:56.358 --> 00:09:01.198
But, there are some nuances, some rules to be aware of.

00:09:02.578 --> 00:09:07.598
A real cooked haggis must be used, and the haggis cannot break.

00:09:08.248 --> 00:09:13.128
If it splits in mid air or when it lands, the throw is disqualified.

00:09:14.588 --> 00:09:16.748
And this happens quite a lot.

00:09:17.428 --> 00:09:23.668
After all, a haggis is only held together with a thin lining, so there is real

00:09:23.668 --> 00:09:30.010
skill in throwing it a long distance but so that the landing is relatively gentle.

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:34.490
And if you are wondering what the world record for haggis hurling

00:09:34.490 --> 00:09:39.750
is, it is 66 metres, which is quite impressive if you ask me.

