00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:26.755
It’s called Irn-Bru, and you can recognise it by its bright orange colour.

00:11:27.830 --> 00:11:31.020
And if you are thinking, hmm, delicious, a kind of

00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:35.790
orange-tasting soda, nope, it doesn’t taste like oranges at all.

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:43.270
I actually quite like it, and I used to drink it a lot as a child, but it has such a

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:48.610
strange taste that it took me quite a while to figure out how to describe it to you.

00:11:49.910 --> 00:11:55.330
I looked through various forums to see how other people described it, and one of the most

00:11:55.360 --> 00:12:01.830
popular comments was that it tastes “kinda like rust and battery acid and it's magic.”

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:08.640
It tastes a little bit like bubblegum, a little bit of lemon, but looks highly

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:13.370
radioactive and tastes like nothing else I’ve tasted anywhere outside Scotland.

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:17.140
And in Scotland, it is exceptionally popular.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:22.640
It is the best-selling drink in the entire country, outselling Coke and Pepsi.

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:29.570
And its recipe, according to folklore at least, is an incredibly closely guarded secret.

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:35.550
Only three people in the company know the exact recipe, and they are never allowed

00:12:35.560 --> 00:12:39.810
to travel together, in case there is an accident and the recipe is lost forever.

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:45.350
So, if you happen to be travelling to Scotland and you see people drinking

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:49.600
what looks like it could be radioactive fluid, that’s what’s going on.

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:54.070
And I would certainly recommend that you try it yourself, as it

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:57.360
is pretty hard to come by anywhere outside the Scottish borders.

00:12:58.393 --> 00:13:02.640
Right, for our last tradition, I’m going to tell you some unusual

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.680
facts about the national instrument of Scotland, the bagpipes.

00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:11.860
As I said at the start of the episode, I can actually play the bagpipes,

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:15.730
so this is something I can tell you about from firsthand experience.

00:13:16.790 --> 00:13:21.000
In case you don’t know what I’m talking about, the bagpipes are a

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:25.550
musical instrument made up of a bag with several tubes coming out of it.

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:32.670
To be precise, one tube where you blow air in, three tubes that sit over your shoulder,

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:38.610
called drones, and another tube that you hold with both hands and play a tune with.

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:44.860
It's not an easy instrument to play, you need to properly manage blowing into the bag

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:51.430
and squeezing it with your left arm, but when you do it properly, it sounds like this.

00:14:07.114 --> 00:14:12.694
So, to finish up this episode, here are five unusual facts about the bagpipes.

00:14:13.834 --> 00:14:17.314
Firstly, the bagpipes can never be silent.

00:14:18.204 --> 00:14:23.304
Unlike almost any other instrument, you can’t stop making noise when you are playing, there is

00:14:23.324 --> 00:14:29.614
always the background noise, the drone, and the noise of the chanter, the one that makes the tune.

00:14:31.054 --> 00:14:36.244
Secondly, bagpipes were traditionally made from the skin of an entire

00:14:36.274 --> 00:14:40.364
animal, with the pipes attached to where the neck and head would have been.

00:14:41.478 --> 00:14:47.214
Thirdly, as you may know, forms of bagpipes exist in many different countries.

00:14:47.674 --> 00:14:52.644
France, Spain, Italy, Poland they all have different forms of bagpipes,

00:14:52.804 --> 00:14:56.134
and there are similar kinds of instruments all over the world.

00:14:57.564 --> 00:15:04.114
Fourth, and this in fact came as news to me, alongside myself, the famous and not

00:15:04.124 --> 00:15:10.144
particularly pleasant Roman emperor, Nero, was said to have been a skilled bagpiper, and

00:15:10.324 --> 00:15:15.754
played a form of bagpipes not so dissimilar to the Scottish “Great Highland bagpipe”.

00:15:17.204 --> 00:15:23.264
And for number five, I’m going to give you a fact that you won’t find anywhere else online.

00:15:24.734 --> 00:15:27.504
There is a kind of whisky called Glenmorangie.

00:15:28.034 --> 00:15:31.374
It's a very famous, high quality whisky, made just

00:15:31.404 --> 00:15:34.734
outside a town called Tain in the north of Scotland.

00:15:35.484 --> 00:15:38.754
You can visit the distillery and see how the whisky is made.

00:15:39.694 --> 00:15:43.144
The distillery employs many people in the area, including

00:15:43.154 --> 00:15:47.654
a man called Jimmy, who was also my bagpipe teacher.

00:15:49.404 --> 00:15:54.954
Jimmy was the nightwatchman, so it was his job to monitor everything in the

00:15:54.954 --> 00:15:59.624
distillery during the night, to make sure that nothing went wrong overnight.

00:16:00.494 --> 00:16:04.124
And Jimmy would spend his evenings walking up and down the

00:16:04.124 --> 00:16:07.604
distillery floor, playing the bagpipes to pass the time.

00:16:08.984 --> 00:16:14.734
And given that Glenmorangie whisky is 10 years old or more, if you have drunk

00:16:14.774 --> 00:16:21.634
Glenmorangie at any point in the last 20 years or so, in all probability that whisky

00:16:21.824 --> 00:16:27.104
has been aged to the sound of a man called Jimmy MacLeod playing the bagpipes.

